===from:Ryan Hilton
===date:Wed Sep 24 14:02:43 2003
===subject:Antifederalists
===message:Could you call those who opposed ratifying the Constitution 'states righters'"? In what way did the Articles protect the power of the states over the federal government under the Constitution? Do you think states should have more power than the federal government? Finally, do you think the Constitution went against revolutionary principles or fulfilled them?---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Surely one could call antifederalists "state's righters" or even to a further extent, "my righters."  They were concerned that a strong central government would impose such restrictions on liberty as did the British pre-revolution, limiting the rights that they thought they had to own slaves and trade as they wished.
The Articles of Confederation did no more to protect the states' rights than it did to enforce national policy.  This "protection" of states' rights was only due to a lack of control from a centralized government that had in no way the right to regulate.......well.....anything!  States were printing their own money, imposing their own regulations on trade(which varied from state to state), and this caused much unrest in the colonies which the national government could do nothing about!
I do not think that states should have more power than the national government.  Things seem to be going pretty well to me.  I don't know in any moral case where the government would come in and restrict some of my rights as a Georgian..........maybe tell me that I could not eat peaches?
The Constitution most definately did not go against the principles that sparked the revolutionary war, after all if there is NO government, then what do you have? Anarchy.  Thomas Paine said "government in its best state is a necessary evil."
=========yorg=========
