===message:Those who were opposed to ratifying the Constitution could be call "state righters," because they felt that the interests of the state may be overwhelmed by that of a federal goverment.  The last thing the colonist wanted was to go back to a oppressive goverment. However, those opposed to a national goverment were not able to see th "bigger picture" in terms of running a country.

The Articles protected the rights of the states over the ferderal goverment in the Constitution by creating a system of checks and balances that ensured that no one brach of the federal goverment would get too powerful.  It also allowed for each state to have representatives in the two houses of the ledislative branch (2 from each state in the senate, and a number equal to population or wealth of a state in the house).  State goverments also keep certain rights that federal goverment could not impede in.  The first amendment of the Constitution also granted a enormous amount of protect to the people of America more than any nation before it.

In my opinion I do not feel that the states should have more rights than the federal goverment.  I feel that had our natinal goverment not aquired the amount of power that it has many positive things such as the civil rights acts may have not occurred.  Though the founder of the Constitution may have never dreamed of the power that our federal goverment has today I think it would make them proud to see that their system has worked in many ways for many people (even those who it may not have been intended to work for).  

I believe do not believe that the Constituion went against the revolutionary principles, I believe that the constitution was the best rememdy for the new and troubled nation.  Those who were opposed to it had valid reasons to be however their position did nothing to help the needs of the people in the country.  The Constitution gave the fundemental rights that John Locke spoke of to every free, white man in America (and eventally minorities and women as well).  The Constitution insured rights and allowed for growth and amemdments with representation for each state.  The Constitution and it's blueprint of a federal goverment was the least oppressive system that could have been created.  The people who were opposed did so out of selfish reasons, not out of interest of the people as a whole.
