===from:Nathaniel M. Smith
===date:Fri Oct 10 13:16:45 2003
===subject:States' Righters
===message:The rebellion against England was not merely against a powerful government; rather, it was fought against taxation without representation.  "Virtual representation," which the colonies supposedly had in Parliament, simply did not serve the practical purpose of allowing colonists to voice their opinions and concerns through due process in the English legislature.
<br><br>
The prevalent economic theory of the age was, of course, mercantalism.  The measure of a country's wealth was directly proportional to the amount of bullion held by that country.  The only manner in which a country could be made richer was by the acquisition of more bullion, and as the amount of gold and silver on the planet is fixed, the best means by which a country could strengthen itself while simultaneously weakening competitive neighbors was to take bullion from other countries.  Thusly, the English pirates who preyed on Spanish galleons came about, and the French and English fought each other incessantly on the high seas and in both the new world and the old, as well as in the far East, for control of global trade routes and economic supremacy.
<br><br>
The role of a country's colonies, according to mercantalist theories, is simply to serve the economic purpose of the mother country, and the manner in which it is to do so is twofold: by supplying raw goods and by providing a market for manufactured products.  
<br><br>
Obviously, the colonists had a different view of themselves by 1776; they were interested in empowering themselves, not in empowering England.  Thus, we have the stage set for revolution; the formation of a central government was not contrary to the motives underlying the American War for Independance.  The revolutionaries were not anarchists who wanted to abolish all government; neither is the opposition of tyranny the negation of any and all central government whatsoever.  Most of the politically learned revolutionaries realized that global survival alongside European nations with powerful central governments would necessitate a central government to oversee the nation as a whole.  
<br><br>
We certainly would have had a vastly different history if the states' rights had remained supreme to any central government.  What is today a (or perhaps the) superpower nation on this planet would instead be a second version of Europe, a collection of relatively small countries, each completely independent of each other.
<br><br>
That's certainly something to think about.
=========yorg=========
