===from:Ian Esson
===date:Tue Oct 14 13:17:04 2003
===subject:Ratification of the constitution
===message:<b>Could you call those who opposed ratifying the Constitution 'states righters'"?</b> <P>
<br>
Yes. At the time of the ratification the only unifying thread between the states was that they had a common enemy. They were still self-seeking capitalists who were bent on seeing their own states as the leading trading ports. The mere fact that they already had their own constitutions leads you to believe that once the British were defeated it would be business as usual – each operating as it’s own entity.  I also believe that some still had the fear that a central government would only be a replacement of the monarchy by the now American elite. <P>
<br>
<B>In what way did the Articles protect the power of the states over the federal government under the Constitution?</B><BR>
<br>
The main clause that protected the states was that there had to be a general consensus before any act of congress could be done. <P>
<br>
 <b>Do you think states should have more power than the federal government?</B><P>
<br>
No. This be tantamount to a feudal system, a major step back and would eventually end up with what we see in Europe where each little serfdom started declaring themselves a separate country. <P>
<br>
<b> Finally, do you think the Constitution went against revolutionary principles or fulfilled them?</b><P>
<br>
A big yes. Although the underlining  reason for the revolution was purely economic, the leaders used the guise of liberty and freedom as a rallying cry. However, in the first draft of the declaration of independence the clause that accused King George of forcing slaves African slaves on the colonies was deleted. [pg 190]. This was necessary because the colonists had no intensions diminishing there free labor force. <BR>They also stated that all men were born with fundamental rights – that would include the slaves and underclass that were born in the colonies. They stated that if all people were n the same then they had the same rights, this is why the slaves could not be class as people but rather as livestock and farm equipment. Also the claim that government should represent the people but a representation of the majority of the people was not included in the discussions. Instead it was the land owners and businessmen whose interests was to be protected.  These are just a few  examples of the hypocrisy that existed.  

=========yorg=========
