===message:I personally would surely have called those who were opposed to ratifying the Constitution “states righters”. That’s because their main reasons for not wanting ratification was because they wanted to keep the political power within the states instead of with an outside central government. Which is understandable, who would want to give up power which when in use will personally affect you? By giving judicial authority and allowing authority over a state’s constitution by their federal courts, the articles protected the power of the states. The Connecticut Compromise also protected the powers of the state. Instead of feeling as if smaller (population) states were lead by the larger states all had an almost equal degree of say in how power would be used: such as collection of taxes and the regulation of foreign commerce. I tend to be a fence sitter myself so it’s hard to say if the states should have more power than the federal government. It all depends on the circumstances of the time. I believe that there needs to be a balance of power between the two. The federal government could unwittingly pass legislation that would be detrimental to individual states but have a positive effect on others. Without the individual states having the power to challenge those legislations nothing could be done. Then again that can lead to a whole other set of problems. If each state is somewhat balanced with the federal government when it comes to power they would have the ability, if they ever felt like it, to constantly disrupt governmental actions. The constitution both went against revolutionary principles and fulfilled them. When it came to human equality it without a doubt went against revolutionary principles. Then with representation of the people it fulfilled them 
